04211nam a22005415i 9780773552401DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20172017xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735524017 a10.1515/97807735524012doi  a(DE-B1597)657443  a(OCoLC)1015239877  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aBX9001 7aREL0970002bisacsh04a285.2712231 aMcKim, Denis, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBoundless Dominion :bProvidence, Politics, and the Early Canadian Presbyterian Worldview /cDenis McKim. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource :b6 b&w images, 2 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in the History of Religion ;v2800tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tSeeing Things the Presbyterian Way -- tBecoming Presbyterian -- tProvidence -- tIsrael and Empire -- tSlavery and Liberty -- tPolitics -- tTwo Swords -- tChristian Leviathan -- tNature -- tWandering in the Wilderness -- tGod's Garden -- tHistory -- tSaving John Knox's House -- tThe Pulse of the Past -- tBoundless Dominion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the twenty-first century, the word Presbyterian is virtually synonymous with “austere” and “parochial.” These associations are by no means historically unfounded, as early Canadian Presbyterians insisted on Sabbath observance and had a penchant for inter- and intra-denominational disagreement. However, many other ideas circulated within this religious community’s collective psyche. Boundless Dominion delves into the elaborate worldview that galvanized nineteenth-century Canadian Presbyterianism. Denis McKim uncovers a vibrant print culture and Presbyterian support for such initiatives as Indigenous evangelism, temperance advocacy, and anti-slavery activism and finds that many of the denomination’s characteristics contrast sharply with its dour and quarrelsome reputation. Tracing the themes of providence, politics, nature, and history in Presbyterian communities across five provinces, from Prince Edward Island, Nova Scotia, and New Brunswick to Lower and Upper Canada, this book reveals that at the heart of this denomination lay a desire to facilitate God’s dominion and to promote Protestant piety across northern North America and beyond. Through an innovative approach to the study of religious ideas, Boundless Dominion highlights the permeability of borders and the myriad ways in which nineteenth-century Canada – including its Presbyterian community – shaped and was shaped by interactions with the wider world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPresbyterian ChurchzCanadaxHistoryy19th century. 0aPresbyterianszCanadaxHistory. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / Presbyterian.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311127365508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017z978311127619940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780773552401?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773552401423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773552401/original  a978-3-11-127365-5  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-127619-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles